<?xml version="1.0" encoding="utf-8"?>
<!--
================================================================================
  FS25_SlurryPipeSystem — Vehicle Configuration Reference
  Oscar Mods
================================================================================
  This file is documentation only. It is not loaded by the mod.

  SPS supports TWO ways to add a vehicle:

    1. INTERNAL  - Vehicle config lives inside the SPS mod folder.
                   Used for the stock fleet shipped with SPS.
                   Path: configs/vehicleConfigs/<name>/fillPoints.xml

    2. EMBEDDED  - Vehicle config lives inside the modder's own vehicle XML
                   as a <slurryPipeSystem> element under the <vehicle> root.
                   Used by third-party mods to ship SPS-ready vehicles
                   without ever touching the SPS mod folder.

  Both paths use IDENTICAL element schema. The only difference is location.
  Embedded configs win over internal manifest entries for the same vehicle.
================================================================================
-->

<slurryPipeSystemReference>


    <!-- ========================================================================
         INTERNAL CONFIG - FOLDER STRUCTURE & MANIFEST
    =========================================================================

    FS25_SlurryPipeSystem/
    └── configs/
        ├── spsConfigManifest.xml           ← lists every supported vehicle/placeable
        ├── couplerAnimations.xml           ← bundled coupler animations library
        │
        ├── data/                           ← stock fleet (mirrors game's data/ paths)
        │   └── vehicles/
        │       └── <vendor>/<model>/
        │           ├── fillPoints.xml      ← vehicle SPS config
        │           └── nodeTree.i3d        ← SPS nodes for this vehicle
        │
        └── mods/                           ← third-party fleet (mirrors mods/ paths)
            └── <FS25_ModFolderName>/
                ├── fillPoints.xml
                └── nodeTree.i3d

    The bundled folder structure mirrors the runtime path of each vehicle.
    Each vehicle has a manifest entry of the form:

        <vehicle path="data/vehicles/kaweco/profi2/profi2.xml"/>
        <vehicle path="mods/FS25_Pichon_BMIX80/BMIX.xml"/>

    The "path" attribute must EXACTLY match the tail of the runtime vehicle's
    configFileName (case-insensitive). When the match succeeds, SPS opens the
    bundled fillPoints.xml from a path computed by:

        1. Take the manifest path
        2. Strip the trailing XML filename
        3. Prepend "configs/"
        4. Append "fillPoints.xml"

    Example:
        path="data/vehicles/kaweco/profi2/profi2.xml"
          → configs/data/vehicles/kaweco/profi2/fillPoints.xml

        path="mods/FS25_Pichon_BMIX80/BMIX.xml"
          → configs/mods/FS25_Pichon_BMIX80/fillPoints.xml

    ── OPTIONAL configFolder OVERRIDE ───────────────────────────────────────

    If a mod ships multiple XMLs in the same folder (e.g. mods/X/cab.xml and
    mods/X/trailer.xml), auto-derivation would collide on the same bundled
    fillPoints folder. Use the optional configFolder attribute to declare
    each entry's bundled location independently:

        <vehicle path="mods/X/cab.xml"
                 configFolder="mods/X/cab"/>
        <vehicle path="mods/X/trailer.xml"
                 configFolder="mods/X/trailer"/>

        → configs/mods/X/cab/fillPoints.xml
        → configs/mods/X/trailer/fillPoints.xml

    The "path" attribute always matches the runtime configFileName. The
    "configFolder" attribute (when present) overrides where the bundled
    fillPoints.xml lives under configs/.

    ======================================================================== -->


    <!-- ========================================================================
         BUNDLED VS EMBEDDED — WHEN TO USE WHICH
    =========================================================================

    INTERNAL/BUNDLED is for vehicles SPS itself supports out of the box.
    The vehicle XML stays untouched (third-party or stock); the fillPoints.xml
    and nodeTree.i3d live inside the SPS mod folder. SPS knows about the
    vehicle via a manifest entry.

    EMBEDDED is for third-party modders shipping SPS-ready vehicles. The
    modder adds a <slurryPipeSystem> block directly inside their vehicle XML.
    No SPS-side files needed. No manifest entry needed. The block self-
    contains everything: pipe couplings, coupler animations, fill arms.

    Embedded ALWAYS wins over manifest. If both exist for the same
    configFileName, the embedded block is used. This lets modders ship
    their own version of any vehicle without conflicting with stock
    SPS support for the same vehicle name.

    ======================================================================== -->


    <!-- ========================================================================
         EMBEDDED CONFIG - INSIDE THE MODDER'S VEHICLE XML
    =========================================================================

    A modder ships their vehicle with a <slurryPipeSystem> element directly
    under <vehicle> in the vehicle's main XML. SPS detects this element at
    register time (before the manifest lookup) and uses the embedded block.

    Example modder XML:

        <vehicle ...>
            ... vanilla vehicle elements ...

            <slurryPipeSystem>
                <flow litersPerSecond="2000"/>
                <pump selfPowered="true"/>
                <pipeCouplings>
                    <pipeCoupling id="1" mountNodeName="myCoupler01" .../>
                </pipeCouplings>
                <couplerAnimations>
                    <couplerAnimation id="1" name="myClamp">
                        <part node="myClampHandle" .../>
                    </couplerAnimation>
                </couplerAnimations>
            </slurryPipeSystem>

            ... more vanilla vehicle elements ...
        </vehicle>

    For embedded configs, ALL nodes referenced by name are looked up inside
    the modder's own vehicle i3d. No nodeTree.i3d file is loaded. Modders
    typically i3d-map the SPS nodes alongside their other vehicle nodes.

    Embedded ALWAYS wins. If both an internal config exists for the same
    configFileName AND the vehicle XML contains <slurryPipeSystem>, the
    embedded block is used. Multiple modder versions of the same vehicle
    (same configFileName) coexist independently — each instance reads
    its own XML.

    ======================================================================== -->


    <!-- ========================================================================
         NODE TREE — i3d SETUP (INTERNAL CONFIG ONLY)
    =========================================================================

    For internal configs, all SPS nodes are authored in a separate nodeTree
    i3d file placed alongside the fillPoints.xml. The nodeTree is loaded via
    loadI3DFile (not cloned) at register time and linked into the vehicle
    scene hierarchy.

    Do NOT use cloneSharedI3DNode for nodeTree files — cloning breaks skin
    bindings.

    EXCEPTION: Conduit pump vehicles (pump conduit="true") have their coupling
    nodes authored directly in the vehicle's own i3d. No nodeTree is needed
    and the <nodeTree> element should be omitted from their fillPoints.xml.

    For EMBEDDED configs there is no nodeTree concept — all node names resolve
    against the modder's own vehicle i3d directly.

    ── NODE TREE STRUCTURE (internal configs) ────────────────────────────────

    nodeTree root (TransformGroup)
    │
    ├── effectNode (TransformGroup)              ← optional, for fill arm vehicles
    │   └── effect (TransformGroup)              ← PipeEffect shape node
    │       └── pipeEffectSmoke (TransformGroup) ← smoke/particle emitter
    │
    ├── fillArms (TransformGroup)
    │   ├── SPS_fillArmCentre01                  ← OPEN_PIT nozzle centre
    │   ├── SPS_fillArmUpper01                   ← OPEN_PIT upper detection
    │   ├── SPS_fillArmLower01                   ← OPEN_PIT lower detection
    │   ├── SPS_fillArmTip01                     ← RUBBER_BOOT tip node
    │   └── (repeat pattern for additional arms)
    │
    └── pipeCouplers (TransformGroup)
        ├── SPS_pipeCoupler01
        │   └── SPS_pipeCoupler01Arcs
        │       ├── SPS_pipeCoupler01Arc01       ← arc detection node left
        │       └── SPS_pipeCoupler01Arc02       ← arc detection node right
        ├── SPS_pipeCoupler02
        │   └── SPS_pipeCoupler02Arcs
        │       ├── SPS_pipeCoupler02Arc01
        │       └── SPS_pipeCoupler02Arc02
        └── (repeat for SPS_pipeCoupler03 etc. if required)

    ── NODE PLACEMENT RULES ──────────────────────────────────────────────────

    SPS_pipeCouplerXX
        Place at the physical centre of the coupling mouth.
        Rotation: local Z-axis pointing outward away from the barrel.

    SPS_pipeCouplerXXArcs (group node) and Arc01 / Arc02
        Place symmetrically either side of the coupler mouth:
            1.5m left and right in local X, 2.5m forward in local Z.
        These define the arc detection triangle used to confirm a pipe end
        is close enough and angled correctly to connect.

    SPS_fillArmCentre
        Place at the nozzle tip centre.
        Used to determine the XZ position for slurry surface height sampling.

    SPS_fillArmUpper
        Place 0.3–0.5m above the nozzle tip.
        Must enter the store fill volume (trigger box) for connection to register.

    SPS_fillArmLower
        Place at or below the nozzle tip.
        Must be below the current slurry surface Y for flow to begin.
        If the surface drops below this node, flow stops automatically.

    SPS_fillArmTip
        RUBBER_BOOT and RUBBER_BOOT_PIT arms only.
        Place exactly at the nozzle tip.
        Used for proximity and angle checks against rubber boot port nodes.

    effect / pipeEffectSmoke
        Place at the point where slurry visually discharges.
        The PipeEffect streams from this node toward the slurry surface.
        pipeEffectSmoke is repositioned dynamically as stream length changes.

    SPS_rubberBootLowerXX / SPS_rubberBootUpperXX
        Place at the lower and upper bounds of the rubber boot opening on
        the vehicle. A connecting fill arm tip must fall between these two Y
        positions, within XZ proximity, for the arm to be considered docked.

    rearControlNode (or any name declared in <pumpControl>)
        Place at the rear of the vehicle where the player stands to access
        the walkaround pump control (selfPowered or conduit vehicles only).

    ======================================================================== -->


    <!-- ========================================================================
         <slurryPipeSystem> ROOT ELEMENT
    =========================================================================

    All SPS configuration for a vehicle lives inside a single
    <slurryPipeSystem> element. For internal configs this is the root of
    fillPoints.xml. For embedded configs this is a child of <vehicle>.

    <slurryPipeSystem agitatorOnly="bool">
        <nodeTree filename="nodeTree.i3d"/>            (internal only)
        <flow .../>
        <pump .../>
        <sounds>...</sounds>
        <fillArms>...</fillArms>
        <pipeCouplings>...</pipeCouplings>
        <rubberBootPorts>...</rubberBootPorts>
        <pumpControls>...</pumpControls>
        <agitator tipNode="..."/>
        <couplerAnimations>...</couplerAnimations>     (optional)
    </slurryPipeSystem>

    ATTRIBUTES on <slurryPipeSystem>:

    agitatorOnly        true = vehicle is purely an agitator and should not
                        register pump/coupling/arm logic. Used for dedicated
                        agitator implements that have no fill capability.
                        Default: false.

    ======================================================================== -->


    <!-- ========================================================================
         <nodeTree>
    =========================================================================

    <nodeTree filename="nodeTree.i3d"/>

    filename    Path to the nodeTree i3d relative to this fillPoints.xml.
                Internal configs only. Omit entirely for:
                    - Conduit pump vehicles whose nodes live in the vehicle i3d.
                    - Embedded configs (the modder's vehicle i3d is used directly).

    ======================================================================== -->


    <!-- ========================================================================
         <flow>
    =========================================================================

    <flow litersPerSecond="N"/>

    litersPerSecond     Base transfer rate in litres per second at full pump.
                        Typical range: 500–2000.
                        Applies to all fill arms and pipe coupling transfers.

    ======================================================================== -->


    <!-- ========================================================================
         <pump>
    =========================================================================

    <pump selfPowered="bool" conduit="bool"/>

    selfPowered="true"  Vehicle has its own pump independent of PTO.
                        Used for self-propelled or electric-pump trailers.
                        The walkaround pumpControl activatable becomes available
                        at the rear of the vehicle.

    conduit="true"      Vehicle is a pass-through pump (PTO Slurry Pump).
                        No fill unit — slurry moves directly between two
                        couplings. Direction set from cab. Either coupling
                        can be inlet or outlet — the pump has no fixed side.
                        flowDirection on connected store couplings is still
                        respected and will block incorrect flow.
                        Pipe chains cannot be laid FROM conduit pump couplings —
                        pipes must be connected TO them.

    Omit <pump/> entirely for standard PTO-driven tankers with no special pump.

    ======================================================================== -->


    <!-- ========================================================================
         <sounds>
    =========================================================================

    <sounds>
        <engineLoop
            file="..."
            linkNode="..."
            innerRadius="N"
            outerRadius="N"
        />
    </sounds>

    file            Path to a .gls sound file. $data/ paths are valid.
    linkNode        Node name in the vehicle hierarchy to attach the sound to.
    innerRadius     Distance in metres at which the sound plays at full volume.
    outerRadius     Distance in metres at which the sound fades to silence.

    Provides a looping pump/engine sound for selfPowered vehicles.
    Omit the <sounds> block entirely for PTO-driven vehicles.

    ======================================================================== -->


    <!-- ========================================================================
         <fillArms>
    =========================================================================

    <fillArms>
        <fillArm
            id="N"
            tipType="OPEN_PIT|RUBBER_BOOT|RUBBER_BOOT_PIT"
            centreNodeName="..."
            upperNodeName="..."
            lowerNodeName="..."
            tipNodeName="..."
            fillUnitIndex="N"
        />
    </fillArms>

    id                  Unique integer ID for this arm within the vehicle.

    tipType
        OPEN_PIT        Arm dips into an open slurry pit or store surface.
                        Requires: centreNodeName, upperNodeName, lowerNodeName.
                        Upper node must enter the store fill volume trigger.
                        Lower node must be below the slurry surface Y for flow.

        RUBBER_BOOT     Arm nozzle docks physically into a rubber boot port
                        on a building or other vehicle.
                        Requires: tipNodeName.
                        Connection confirmed by proximity and angle to boot nodes.

        RUBBER_BOOT_PIT Combines RUBBER_BOOT physical docking with OPEN_PIT
                        surface detection. Used for enclosed inlet ports that
                        also have a visible slurry surface below.
                        Requires: tipNodeName, centreNodeName, upperNodeName,
                                  lowerNodeName.

    centreNodeName      Node at nozzle centre for XZ surface sampling (OPEN_PIT).
    upperNodeName       Node above nozzle — enters store fill volume (OPEN_PIT).
    lowerNodeName       Node at nozzle tip — must be below surface Y (OPEN_PIT).
    tipNodeName         Node at tip for proximity/angle docking (RUBBER_BOOT).
    fillUnitIndex       Vehicle fill unit to fill or discharge. Default: 1.

    Leave <fillArms/> self-closing if this vehicle has no fill arms.

    ======================================================================== -->


    <!-- ========================================================================
         <pipeCouplings>
    =========================================================================

    <pipeCouplings>
        <pipeCoupling
            id="N"
            mountNodeName="..."
            valveType="MANUAL|HYDRAULIC|NONE"
            maxPipeLength="N.N"
            fillUnitIndex="N"
            valveFromRearControl="bool"
            connector="male|female"
            connectorAnimation="N"
            valveAnimation="N"
        />
    </pipeCouplings>

    id                      Unique integer ID for this coupling within the vehicle.

    mountNodeName           Node name of the coupling mount point.
                            Internal: a node in the nodeTree.
                            Embedded: a node in the modder's vehicle i3d.
                            Conduit vehicles: directly in the vehicle i3d.

                            Arc detection nodes must exist as children:
                                <mountNodeName>Arcs
                                    <mountNodeName>Arc01
                                    <mountNodeName>Arc02

    valveType
        MANUAL              Valve is opened by the player at the coupling
                            using long press R. Standard for tankers.

        HYDRAULIC           Valve is opened from the cab via SPS_TOGGLE_FLOW.
                            Used for conduit pumps and hydraulically controlled
                            trailers. Player at the coupling is only offered
                            disconnect — no valve prompts. Pipe chains cannot
                            be laid from this coupling.

        NONE                No valve. Flow begins immediately when connected
                            and the pump is running. Use with valveFromRearControl="true".

    maxPipeLength           Maximum distance in metres for a bez pipe or chain
                            terminus to connect to this coupling. Typical: 4.0–8.0.

    fillUnitIndex           Vehicle fill unit index. Default: 1.
                            Not applicable for conduit vehicles.

    valveFromRearControl    true = valve state is controlled by the rear
                            pumpControl activatable rather than manually at
                            the coupling. Pair with valveType="NONE" for
                            self-powered trailers.

    connector               "male" or "female". Controls which end of the
                            connecting bez pipe is shown at this coupling.
                            The pipe visual matches both ends to the coupling
                            connector type at each end. Default: "male".

    connectorAnimation      Optional animation id from <couplerAnimations>.
                            Plays forward when a pipe connects to this coupling,
                            reverse when it disconnects. Used for clamp / collar
                            visuals that close on connect and open on disconnect.
                            Omit if the coupling has no connect/disconnect
                            animation.

    valveAnimation          Optional animation id from <couplerAnimations>.
                            Plays forward when this coupling's valve opens,
                            reverse when it closes. Used for valve handle
                            rotations. Omit if the coupling has no valve handle.
                            Works for valveType="MANUAL", and also for
                            valveType="NONE" with valveFromRearControl="true"
                            (animates when the cab valve toggles).

    ======================================================================== -->


    <!-- ========================================================================
         <rubberBootPorts>
    =========================================================================

    <rubberBootPorts>
        <rubberBootPort
            id="N"
            lowerNodeName="..."
            upperNodeName="..."
            valveType="MANUAL|HYDRAULIC|NONE"
            fillUnitIndex="N"
        />
    </rubberBootPorts>

    id              Unique integer ID for this port.

    lowerNodeName   Lower boundary node of the rubber boot docking zone.
    upperNodeName   Upper boundary node of the rubber boot docking zone.
                    A connecting fill arm tip must fall between the Y positions
                    of these two nodes, and within XZ proximity, for docking.

    valveType       Controls how the port valve is opened.
                    NONE = port is always open when an arm is docked.

    fillUnitIndex   Vehicle fill unit index. Default: 1.

    ======================================================================== -->


    <!-- ========================================================================
         <pumpControls>
    =========================================================================

    <pumpControls>
        <pumpControl
            id="N"
            nodeName="..."
            radius="N.N"
        />
    </pumpControls>

    id              Unique integer ID.
    nodeName        Node name in the vehicle hierarchy where the walkaround
                    pump control activatable appears. Player must be within
                    radius of this node to see pump/valve/direction prompts.
    radius          Activation radius in metres. Default: 1.5.

    Omit <pumpControls/> entirely for vehicles that use in-cab controls only
    (PTO-driven tankers without selfPowered or conduit pump).

    ======================================================================== -->


    <!-- ========================================================================
         <agitator>
    =========================================================================

    <agitator tipNode="..."/>

    tipNode         Node name where the agitator's mechanical tip operates.
                    The manager uses this to apply agitation effects to any
                    fill plane the tip is currently inserted into.
                    Omit if this vehicle is not an agitator.

    ======================================================================== -->


    <!-- ========================================================================
         <couplerAnimations>
    =========================================================================

    <couplerAnimations>
        <couplerAnimation id="N" name="...">
            <part
                node="..."
                startTime="N.N"
                endTime="N.N"
                startRot="X Y Z"
                endRot="X Y Z"
                startTrans="X Y Z"
                endTrans="X Y Z"
            />
            <part .../>
            ...
        </couplerAnimation>
    </couplerAnimations>

    Each <couplerAnimation> is referenced from <pipeCoupling> by id (via
    connectorAnimation="N" or valveAnimation="N"). Animations are scoped
    to the vehicle that declares them — there is no global namespace.
    Modder A's id="1" and Modder B's id="1" are independent.

    For internal configs the bundled file configs/couplerAnimations.xml
    is used. For embedded configs, the modder declares animations inline
    inside their <slurryPipeSystem> block.

    couplerAnimation
        id          Unique integer id within this <couplerAnimations> block.
                    Referenced by <pipeCoupling connectorAnimation="N"/> and
                    <pipeCoupling valveAnimation="N"/>.
        name        Human-readable name (logged at load, otherwise unused).

    part            One animated node within this animation. Multiple parts
                    can be combined into a single animation (e.g. two clamp
                    handles closing together).

        node        Node name. Must exist as a descendant of the coupling's
                    mountNode subtree at registration time. Resolved via
                    depth-first search from the mountNode.

        startTime   Animation time in seconds when this part starts moving.
        endTime     Animation time in seconds when this part stops moving.
                    Animation duration is the maximum endTime across all parts.

        startRot    Rotation in DEGREES at startTime. "X Y Z" Euler.
        endRot      Rotation in DEGREES at endTime. Linear interpolation
                    between startRot and endRot during the part's active range.

        startTrans  Translation in METRES at startTime. "X Y Z".
        endTrans    Translation in METRES at endTime.

    Both rotation and translation are optional — declare whichever the part
    needs. Forward play (connect / valve open) animates from start to end.
    Reverse play (disconnect / valve close) animates from end to start.

    ======================================================================== -->

</slurryPipeSystemReference>